[{"id":30065,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A and $\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{I}$","$B$ and $\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{I}$","Addition of $\\mathrm{HNO}_3$ was unnecessary","A was $\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{I}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{I}$ will not respond to silver nitrate test because $\\mathrm{C}$-I bond has a partial double bond character.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":30060,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["3, 3- dimethyl -1- hydroxy cyclohexane","1,1-dimethyl -3- cyclohexanol","3,3- dimethyl -1- cyclohexanol","1,1 - dimethyl -3- hydroxy cyclohexane"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":29706,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6hgnwkiazOYtcHe64Gr1cFp50PMpmyopgzQPJiQfBtw.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/LMF2KQFjzU7DwWssLoa5IHJZ6KfKxByvLq31xUe-q30.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/00CGprxevHggH7GzfktsuESKCZGbf9Tpkic5St8zZdo.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/BA0JcueT9SanAPGSEJc-j2dH7F1bOWnUwmF7_IZZwlI.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bakgE0pUo4o7HkDdiAMItbq15cZevYuAMkNLmUGgItQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\nDue to +M effect of -OMe at para position<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/VAeJQ35teK3n5Qot4fC7PIeMnD68W187gA6UnQvahQM.original.fullsize.png\"><br> Will be most stable among these","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29700,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/lV4_eEbCZUKfCbDs-wghGOFy6dU3e4w6d5ZzULMn9pM.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/QLFAosjOv2NCYUisbMLCYc2r-YB-xAPsC1OoBQSLFXc.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Du9K12ey6g1NdEJS4jzv6VX0QGqxUR68Eg0AKOLDjAw.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/X-LSlbnqf1e0deeNfmJoPwSJ0GNAm-RQ27wBzg-RSew.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://cdn.quizrr.in/question-assets/jee_main_pyq/6rxCwqGsjINdT0tyyhpzmwi-JJhAUn7RPa4Q_fnXJUE.original.fullsize_2.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (24 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29763,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect.","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect.","Both Statement I and Statement II are correct.","Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct."],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Rule 1 :- The longest chain in the molecule will be the parent chain. So, the first thing one should do is to find the longest carbon chain in the molecule.</p><p>Rule 2 :- Find out all the substituents present on the carbon chain. It can be any- from methyl to any alcohol substituent.</p><p>Rule 3 :- Start numbering the parent chain from the end such that the substituent gets the lowest number. This is called the lowest locant rule.</p><p>Rule 4 :- If the substituent occurs more than one time, then the prefix di, tri or tetra is being used with the location of the carbon on which it is present.</p><p>Rule 5 :- If more than one substituents are present and they are different. So, these will be named in alphabetical order.</p><p>In the given compound, hydroxy group is given at position┬Ā<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>7</mn></math>, there is keto group at position┬Ā<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>, carbon chain consists of┬Ā<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>7</mn></math>┬Ācarbon atoms, hence, it is┬Āheptane.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>7</mn></math>-Hydroxyheptan-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>- One is the correct IUPAC name.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29938,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/42f18f0b-a072-4ccb-a70e-637a17e7cd66-image.png\" style=\"width: 227px; height: 221px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5caf9305-83f4-4bd4-9625-0cc295a46d60-image.png\" style=\"width: 202px; height: 54px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1efaf5e0-0ea9-40e9-9c65-eca67fa50e69-image.png\" style=\"width: 204px; height: 162px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fcd2944d-efa0-4cd1-8cef-aa9021ae32a4-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 185px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>It is an example of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;reaction.</p><p>Rate of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>reaction</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>stability</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>carbocation</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></math></p><p>In option 1 carbocation&nbsp;formed after removing halogen is destabilized by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp;effect.</p><p>In option 2 carbocation&nbsp;formed after removing halogen is stabilized by +M effect since lone pair is present at oxygen atom.</p><p>In option 3&nbsp;carbocation&nbsp;formed after removing halogen is stabilized by +M effect of lone pair present on nitrogen atom but lone pair is also in conjugation with benzene ring therefore +M effect is less.</p><p>In option 4&nbsp;carbocation&nbsp;formed after removing halogen is stabilized by +M effect of lone pair present on nitrogen atom and +M effect of nitrogen atom is more than that of oxygen atom. Hence, option 4 is most stable.&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (04 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29887,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munder><msubsup><mi>MnO</mi><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup><mrow><mi>vf</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></munder><mo>+</mo><munder><mrow><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>&#10230;</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>vf</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></munder><msup><mi>Mn</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math></p><p>Mili equ. of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>MnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mmultiscripts><mo>=</mo><mprescripts/><none/><mo>-</mo></mmultiscripts></math>&nbsp;mili equ. of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>[</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>]</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>[</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>]</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mn>5</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mfrac><mtext>&#160;mole&#160;</mtext><mtext>&#160;Lit&#160;</mtext></mfrac></math></p><p>Strength of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>KMnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>158</mn><mfrac><mi>gram</mi><mi>Lit</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>316</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30055,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Diastereo","Optical","Geometric","Structural"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Zbw1GifZzhn7N_vlHoENQhVgNJ1mzR5Vo8Swu4eaAvA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":29799,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A is false but R is true","Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The electron withdrawing groups decreases the acidic nature and&nbsp;The electron releasing&nbsp;groups increases the acidic nature.</p><p>The<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Cl</mi></math> are electron withdrawing while <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> is electron loosing hence acidic strength will be</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8555480f-a48a-4a05-9c68-c541e6b6d237.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 157px;\" /></p><p>On further differentiation the<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8211;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> effect depends on most importantly over distance hence.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6b80bb87-d954-4e77-9a43-81562a1dd606.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 161px;\" /></p><p>The <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></math>&nbsp;has higher <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8211;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> effect as compared to Cl hence reason is correct statement but the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8211;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> effect depends more on distance as compared to power&nbsp;hence&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c9d05d5a-0564-4cf3-9979-38bd04fc88c7.png\" style=\"width: 100px; height: 115px;\" />&nbsp;is stronger acid than&nbsp;&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8bf607cb-e706-4d69-8b91-8cd09560c8b9.png\" style=\"width: 80px; height: 175px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (13 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29850,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b9b58987-c936-48a8-a1c6-7e085772704f-image.png\" style=\"width: 272px; height: 300px;\" /></p><p>Since diazonium ion is a cation hence it is<br />stabilized by electron donating groups and<br />destabilized by electron withdrawing group.<br />Hence Stability order should be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29983,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{O} 2-\\mathrm{C} 3$","O5-C6","$\\mathrm{C} 4-\\mathrm{O} 5$","$\\mathrm{C} 1-\\mathrm{O} 2$"],"answer":1,"solution":"The lone pair of electrons on $\\mathrm{O} 2$ is involved in resonance with $\\mathrm{C}=\\mathrm{C}$. Hence $\\mathrm{O} 2$ will not be protonated.\nThe lone pair of electrons on O5 is not involved in resonance with $\\mathrm{C}=\\mathrm{C}$. Hence, O5 will be protonated. Chloride ion will then attack least substituted $\\mathrm{C}$ atom (C6)\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/oi7P82eSUhNkD19WtmDvBhhQDGvScUfgJilNt1GIzAw.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/xjwevVrVt1h4w4K_hBIH46TlBhTRptRkxRpIKj573GY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 2 Online)","image":null},{"id":29933,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-nitro-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math>-hydroxymethyl-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>-amino benzaldehyde","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>-amino-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math>-hydroxymethyl-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>-nitrogenzaldehyde","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>-amino-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math>-hydroxymethyl-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-nitrobenzaldehyde","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math>-amino-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-formyl-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>-hydroxymethyl nitrogenzene"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/53bd09ff-a9e7-41a7-9e80-636400388fa6-image.png\" style=\"width: 181px; height: 167px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>-Amino-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math>-(hydroxymethyl)-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-nitro benzene carbaldehyde.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (06 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30075,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{NaOH}$","ammonical $\\mathrm{AgNO}_3$","$\\mathrm{Na}$","$\\mathrm{HCl}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8JNCoX4CEo8aPVtwPZksLbtc83g9cafoVBXzcblVoJs.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":29653,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["I $>$ IV $>$ II $>$ V $>$ III","I $>$ II $>$ IV $>$ V $>$ III","IV $>$ I $>$ II $>$ V $>$ III","IV $>$ II $>$ I $>$ III $>$ V"],"answer":2,"solution":"Carbanion stability increases with electron-withdrawing groups (stabilize negative charge) and decreases with electron-donating groups (destabilize negative charge).<br>IV has CHO (strongly electron-withdrawing by inductive effect), most stable.<br>I has Br (weakly electron-withdrawing).<br> II is pure benzyl with resonance from ring.<br> V has CHŌéā (weakly electron-donating).<br> III has OCHŌéā (strongly electron-donating, destabilizes the carbanion). <br>The critical factor is inductive electron-withdrawing ability:<br>CHO > Br > H > CHŌéā > OCHŌéā.<br>Therefore: IV > I > II > V > III.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29936,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f083c4f7-4c51-44a5-95fc-972f50a338bf-image.png\" style=\"width: 94px; height: 181px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ff1c6cd9-ef90-4c6d-b7f9-e4ad52c5083b-image.png\" style=\"width: 139px; height: 158px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1a72d93c-510e-44c4-b8ba-02e229590ea4-image.png\" style=\"width: 193px; height: 158px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d0dd8720-8c08-4f29-bdfd-2a0959c0c299-image.png\" style=\"width: 93px; height: 138px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"Geometrical isomerism arises due to<br />(1) The presence of a restricted rotation (double bond or a ring structure).<br />(2) Two different groups should be attached to any two carbon atoms of restricted rotation.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (05 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30061,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["2- chlorobutane","2- hydroxyopanoic acid","2,3 - dichloropentane","2-3- dichlorobutane"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6ELmZkAZ7YFmxTe5MrnIKE_wEav4otLwO17ckQ0t-s0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":29645,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true"],"answer":0,"solution":"Statement I is true because the $-OCH_3$ group is an electron-donating group. It donates electron density through resonance ($+R$ effect), which delocalizes the positive charge of the carbocation and stabilizes it.<br><br>Statement II is true because the $-NO_2$ group is a strong electron-withdrawing group. It withdraws electron density through resonance ($-R$ effect), which delocalizes the negative charge of the carbanion and stabilizes it.<br><br>Therefore, both Statement I and Statement II are true.<br><br>Answer: Both Statement I and Statement II are true","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (02 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29911,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Statement I is true but statement II is false","Both statement I and statement II are true","Statement I is false but statement II is true","Both statement I and statement II are false"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AgCN</mi></math>&nbsp;both can generate nucleophiles.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AgCN</mi></math>&nbsp;generate isocyanide&nbsp;as a nucleophile but&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KCN</mi></math>&nbsp;cyanide as a nucleophile.&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29682,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["C & D only","B & C only","A & B only","A,B & C only"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2OHxMWywXVAtFrlZxYZUQRxKHcQldOykWz4afmmh2FM.original.fullsize.png\"/><br />In option C are momologoes to each - other and option D are only organic molecule not isomers.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (3 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29674,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["(A)-(IV), (B)-(III), (C)-(II), (D)-(I)","(A)-(I), (B)-(II), (C)-(III), (D)-(IV)","(A)-(III), (B)-(IV), (C)-(I), (D)-(II)","(A)-(II), (B)-(I), (C)-(IV), (D)-(III)"],"answer":0,"solution":"(A) Aniline $-\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}$ : Steam Distillation<br />(B) Glycerol from spent-lye in soap industry - Distillation under reduced pressure<br />(C) Different fraction of crude oil in petroleum industry - Fractional distillation<br />(D) $\\mathrm{CHCl}_3-$ Aniline - Simple distillation","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (4 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29874,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/58ce1ef2-0882-4d78-a20d-4f3a21002a3a-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 193px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/694138fb-3c53-4a2e-bf01-c0c8c3fb1f18-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 196px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/96e5e5a7-0441-402b-9633-00a734d1304d-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 180px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/32f7b045-c748-4048-939e-344905e6431d-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 196px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>A staggered conformation is a chemical conformation of an ethane-like molecule in which the substituents are at the maximum distance from each other. This requires the torsional angle to be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>&nbsp;.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/694138fb-3c53-4a2e-bf01-c0c8c3fb1f18-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 196px;\" /></p><p>In anti conformation the dihedral angle is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>180</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msup></math> (maximum)</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30011,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{B}>\\mathrm{A}>\\mathrm{C}>\\mathrm{D}$","$\\mathrm{D}>\\mathrm{C}>\\mathrm{B}>\\mathrm{A}$","$\\mathrm{A}>\\mathrm{B} > \\mathrm{C} > \\mathrm{D}$","$\\mathrm{B} > \\mathrm{C} > \\mathrm{A} > \\mathrm{D}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"$-\\mathrm{Cl}$ and $-\\mathrm{CH}_3$ groups are $\\mathrm{o}$ and $\\mathrm{p}$ directing. They are electron releasing due to $+\\mathrm{E}$ and $+M$ effects. Further since such groups increase electron density in the nucleus, they facilitate further electrophilic substitution and hence known as activating group. The activating effect of these groups is in order of $-\\mathrm{CH}_3>-\\mathrm{X}$ but chlorine exceptionally deactive the ring due to strong $\\mathrm{- I}$ effect. Hence, it is difficult to carry out substitution in chlorobenzene than in benzene. Further $-\\mathrm{NO}_2$ is a deactivating group hence deactivates the benzene nucleus, i.e. hinder the further substitution. Thus nitrobenzene undergo electrophilic substitution with a great difficulty hence the correct order will be\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/w2cpg9ahh2CiwdZQevO435tktYnENZHOO6tRWbJbNiM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (25 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30032,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{HCOOH}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}(\\mathrm{Cl}) \\mathrm{CO}_2 \\mathrm{H}$","$\\mathrm{ClCH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{COOH}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COOH}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Electron releasing groups (Alkyl groups) de stabilizes conjugate base.\nThe $+$ I effect of $\\mathrm{C}_3 \\mathrm{H}_7$ is less than $-1$ effect of $\\mathrm{Cl}$\n$\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{a}}$ of $\\mathrm{HCOOH}$ is $17.9 \\times 10^{-5}$\n$\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{a}}$ of $\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\underset{\\mathrm{Cl}}{\\mathrm{CH}}-\\mathrm{COOH}$ is $139 \\times 10^{-5}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2011","image":null},{"id":30003,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["2-chloropropanal","2-chloro-2-methylbutane","2-chlorobutane","2-chloropentane"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img alt=\"\" height=\"108\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image1-381cc53b-893b-43a4-95de-f36000ec2a9e.jpg\" width=\"201\" /><br /><br /><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (Optically active)<br /><br /><br /><img alt=\"\" height=\"119\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image2-5e777020-c519-47fe-8587-bb5e679256d6.jpg\" width=\"259\" /><br /><br />(Optically inactive because of <math><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math> groups present on same C atom)<br /><br /><br /><img alt=\"\" height=\"142\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image3-5071142c-64f6-4dbc-84b3-574a9126a71d.jpg\" width=\"249\" /><br /><br /><br /><img alt=\"\" height=\"111\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image4-b58908a8-d110-42f9-a404-a398cf906bd2.jpg\" width=\"338\" /><br /><br /><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong>(Optically active)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":29941,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Given reaction is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;reaction. In&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;reaction</p><p>Rate of reaction&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8733;</mo></math>&nbsp;Stability of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math></p><p>(A)</p><p>&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3d9722bd-b622-4b7c-8274-6d9f6d4b15c4-image.png\" style=\"width: 211px; height: 151px;\" /></p><p>(B)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/363bd30f-3c75-4637-bea9-9b36e352e468-image.png\" style=\"width: 362px; height: 218px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>(C)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8e9cb32e-2742-4b4b-a639-631802e9aa00-image.png\" style=\"width: 356px; height: 98px;\" /></p><p>(D)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/da6bc93f-3c38-4390-99f9-c1aa043e3e37-image.png\" style=\"width: 490px; height: 99px;\" /></p><p>Stability of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ii</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>iv</mi></math></p><p>Reactivity order :&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (04 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29849,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/840381d3-8c78-4993-880d-fe884a2cf09a-image.png\" style=\"width: 90px; height: 100px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/653d8af2-7636-44ec-a24e-cdc3befff748-image.png\" style=\"width: 86px; height: 90px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ca5409b7-a325-4618-b1d3-6de2589ec9ec-image.png\" style=\"width: 151px; height: 90px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e5cae661-3477-41f9-a2e8-5bcfa1bf76b8-image.png\" style=\"width: 151px; height: 90px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Characteristics of aromatic compounds include:<br />- Must be Cyclic and planar<br />- Must have <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></math>&nbsp;electrons <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo></mrow></mfenced></math><br />- Resist Addition but Prefer Substitution.<br />- Must Possess Resonance Energy.<br />Due to severe non-bonded interactions between the internal hydrogen (as shown in figure), the ring assumes non-planar geometry in 10-annulene, hence, it is not an aromatic compound.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1384eaaf-d2a0-42b0-84e6-b770a8a196aa-9755187_S.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 213px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30051,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Chemically reactive","Chemically inactive","Anions","Cations"],"answer":0,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":30016,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$2^{\\circ}>1^{\\circ}>\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{OH}>3^{\\circ}$","$3^{\\circ}>2^{\\circ}>1^{\\circ}>\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{OH}$","$2^{\\circ}>3^{\\circ}>1^{\\circ}>\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{OH}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{OH}>1^{\\circ}>2^{\\circ}>3^{\\circ}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"The order of dehydration among three type of alcohols is $3^{\\circ}>2^{\\circ}>1^{\\circ}>\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{OH}$. This behaviour is related to the relative stabilities of carbocations $\\left(3^{\\circ}>2^{\\circ}>1^{\\circ}\\right)$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":29955,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&gt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&gt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&gt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&gt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&gt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&gt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&gt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&gt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"If the&nbsp;negative charge is delocalised with electron withdrawing group like <math><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>)</mo></math> then stability increase.<br />A) Negative charge is delocalised with <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math> group<br />B) Negative charge is delocalised with carbon of alkene<br />C) Negative charge is localised","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (07 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29646,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$-CONH_2, >C=O, -CHO, -NH_2, -C\\equiv C-$","$-CONH_2, -COOCH_3, -CHO, -NH_2, -OH$","$-CONH_2, -CHO, >C=O, -NH_2, -C\\equiv C-$","$-CONH_2, -CHO, -CN, -NH_2, -C\\equiv C-$"],"answer":2,"solution":"The correct order of decreasing priority for functional groups in IUPAC nomenclature is:<br><br>Carboxylic acids ($-COOH$) $>$ Sulphonic acids ($-SO_3H$) $>$ Esters ($-COOR$) $>$ Acid halides ($-COX$) $>$ Amides ($-CONH_2$) $>$ Nitriles ($-CN$) $>$ Aldehydes ($-CHO$) $>$ Ketones ($>C=O$) $>$ Alcohols ($-OH$) $>$ Thiols ($-SH$) $>$ Amines ($-NH_2$) $>$ Alkynes ($-C\\equiv C-$).<br><br>Checking the given options:<br>Option (A) is incorrect because $-CHO$ has a higher priority than $>C=O$.<br>Option (B) is incorrect because $-COOCH_3$ has a higher priority than $-CONH_2$.<br>Option (C) correctly follows the priority order: $-CONH_2 > -CHO > >C=O > -NH_2 > -C\\equiv C-$.<br>Option (D) is incorrect because $-CN$ has a higher priority than $-CHO$.<br><br>Answer: $-CONH_2, -CHO, >C=O, -NH_2, -C\\equiv C-$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (02 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29660,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["0.21","21","42","0.42"],"answer":2,"solution":"In Kjeldahl's method, nitrogen in the compound is converted to NHŌéā.<br>The ammonia is absorbed and reacts with HŌééSOŌéä according to: $2NH_3 + H_2SO_4 \\rightarrow (NH_4)_2SO_4$.<br>Given that 15 mL of 1 M HŌééSOŌéä was neutralized:<br>Moles of HŌééSOŌéä = 15 ├Ś 10Ōü╗┬│ mol.<br>From stoichiometry, 1 mol HŌééSOŌéä reacts with 2 mol NHŌéā.<br>Therefore, moles of NHŌéā = 2 ├Ś 15 ├Ś 10Ōü╗┬│ = 0.030 mol.<br>Since each NHŌéā contains 1 nitrogen atom:<br>Moles of N = 0.030 mol.<br>Mass of N = 0.030 ├Ś 14 = 0.42 g.<br>Percentage of N in compound = (0.42/1) ├Ś 100 = 42%.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29953,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["methanol <math><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math> -ethoxyphenol <math><mo>&lt;</mo></math> phenol","phenol <math><mo>&lt;</mo></math> methanol <math><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math> -ethoxyphenol","phenol <math><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math> -ethoxyphenol <math><mo>&lt;</mo></math> methanol","methanol <math><mo>&lt;</mo></math> phenol <math><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math> -ethoxyphenol"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/52614462-dc61-43e6-96d9-ed2a6ae9056f.jpeg\" /><br /><br />There is not any resonance in CH3&ndash;OH. Resonance is poor in p-Ethoxyphenol than phenol . So C-OH bond lengh order is: <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></math> &gt;p-Ethoxyphenol &gt; phenol","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29679,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Both Statement I and Statement II are true"],"answer":2,"solution":"Hyper conjugation is permanent effect because external reagent is not required, so Statement-I is false and Statement-II is true. because moore alkyl group, more $\\alpha-H$, so more hyperconjugation which results more stability of carbocation.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (3 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29695,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{C}\\gt\\mathrm{B}\\gt\\mathrm{A}\\gt\\mathrm{D}$","$\\mathrm{A}\\gt\\mathrm{B}\\gt\\mathrm{C}\\gt\\mathrm{D}$","$\\mathrm{B}\\gt\\mathrm{C}\\gt\\mathrm{A}\\gt\\mathrm{D}$","$\\mathrm{C}\\gt\\mathrm{A}\\gt\\mathrm{B}\\gt\\mathrm{D}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5m0WgDRUNU_tQbw3LOgvaoZaH8qq00K6bVuE2mhhIMk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\nSolution :-\nC is aromatic due to $\\oplus \\mathrm{ve}$ charge hence it is most stable\nA have more resonance structure\nB have less resonance structure\nD have only hyper conjugation\nConsider First Aromaticity $>$ Resonance $>$ Hyper conjugation\nAns. D $ < $ B $ < $ A $ < $ C","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29880,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CoCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CoCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>FeCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>FeCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mi>NaCN</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>FeSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>&#10230;</mo><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mi>Fe</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>CN</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mn>6</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mi>Fe</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>CN</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mn>6</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mrow><msub><mi>xH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow></mover><munder><mrow><msub><mi>Fe</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mi>Fe</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>CN</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mn>6</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>.</mo><msub><mi>xH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>Ferric</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>ferrocyanide</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>Prussian</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>blue</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>complex</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></munder></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (01 Sep Shift 2)","image":null}]